SENATE JOINT RESOLUTION 875
By Haile
A RESOLUTION to honor the memory of Donald Kenton Wright of
Sumner County.
WHEREAS, the members of this General Assembly were greatly saddened to learn of
the passing of Donald Kenton Wright; and
WHEREAS, Don Wright was an exemplary public servant and consummate professional
who worked assiduously to improve the quality of life for his fellow citizens in numerous
capacities; and
WHEREAS, born in Louisville, Kentucky, on September 22, 1939, Don Wright was the
son of Joe Willie Wright and Hallie Marie House Wright; he graduated from Goodlettsville High
School in 1958; and
WHEREAS, he went on to serve in the United States Army as a military policeman at the
Raven Rock Mountain Complex, a secure underground nuclear bunker in Pennsylvania known
as "The Little Pentagon," an experience that shaped his strong character and dedication to his
duties as a citizen; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Wright's professional journey included a fulfilling career as a pipefitter
and an educator, teaching drafting at a trade school in Lebanon; his commitment to public
service was evident during his tenure as a Tennessee State Senator from 1992 to 1996 and as
the mayor of Gallatin from 1997 to 2006. Through his leadership, he made a lasting impact on
his community; and
WHEREAS, he was also an accomplished author, leaving behind a literary legacy that
includes titles such as The Woodsman, The Captive, The Last Plantation, and Gone to Texas,
works that reflect his creativity and passion for history and storytelling; and
SJR0875
014132
- 1 -

WHEREAS, Don Wright enjoyed attending church and was a longtime member of First
Baptist Church of Gallatin; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Wright was also deeply devoted to his family, and he always
endeavored to remain true to family values of the highest order; and
WHEREAS, he is survived by his wife of thirty years, Patricia Wright; his brother, David
(Jane) Wright; his grandson, James Kenton Wright; his two great-grandchildren; his brothers-in-
law, Ralph Gregory and Steve (Gayla) Gregory; his sisters-in-law, Peggy (Larry) Ard and Judy
(Harry) Mann; and numerous nieces and nephews; and
WHEREAS, in addition to his parents, he was preceded in death by his daughter,
Candace Elizabeth Wright; brother, Joseph Maxwell Wright; and sister-in-law, Elizabeth Ann
Gregory; and
WHEREAS, Don Wright's indelible spirit and positivity shone brightly throughout his life,
earning him a reputation as someone who was friendly and never met a stranger; and
WHEREAS, it is fitting that the members of this General Assembly should pause to
remember the bountiful life of this exceptional public servant and human being; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE OF THE ONE HUNDRED FOURTEENTH
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE HOUSE OF
REPRESENTATIVES CONCURRING, that we honor the memory of Donald Kenton Wright,
reflecting fondly upon his impeccable character and his stalwart commitment to living the
examined life with courage and conviction.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we express our sympathy and offer our condolences
to the family of Mr. Wright.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
